Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
The classic C interface for obtaining dynamic memory is malloc( )

===============================================================================================
COMPILE :
make
gcc -Wall -g -o malloc_op malloc.c;

===============================================================================================
Executio:

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Memory_Management/malloc$ ./malloc_op 

 Allocated enough memory to hold a treasure_map stucture 
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Memory_Management/malloc$ 


===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
    A successful call to malloc( ) allocates size bytes of memory, and returns a pointer to the
    start of the newly allocated region.
    The contents of the memory are undefined, do not expect the memory to be zeroed. Upon 
    failure, malloc( ) returns NULL. 




